org.jamsim.ascape.navigator

Class SubFolderNode

  • java.lang.Object
    • javax.swing.tree.DefaultMutableTreeNode
      • org.jamsim.ascape.navigator.SubFolderNode
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Cloneable, MutableTreeNode, TreeNode, org.ascape.runtime.swing.navigator.PopupMenuProvider, Saveable

    public class SubFolderNode
extends DefaultMutableTreeNode
implements org.ascape.runtime.swing.navigator.PopupMenuProvider, Saveable
    Navigator node that displays subfolders of nodes for simulation runs. A sub folder can be a run subfolder, eg: "Run 1", "Run 2", .... "All Runs" etc. or a group subfolder (which has it's own run subfolders under it).
    Version:
    $Revision$
    Author:
    Oliver Mannion

        Add a child node directly under the appropriate run subfolder for this node.
        Parameters:
        runNumber - the run number subfolder under which to create the child node. If the run number is ALLRUNS, then it is created under the "All Runs" node.

      • addChildNode

        public void addChildNode(MutableTreeNode newNode,
                String path)
        Add a child node directly under this node, or to a path under this node.
        Parameters:
        newNode - panel view node
        path - a path to a sub folder node, eg: "Base/Means" which represents the folder Means under the folder Base, or just "Base" which will add to the folder Base, or null to add directly under this node.

      • getRunSubFolderNode

        public SubFolderNode getRunSubFolderNode(int runNumber)
        Get the run sub folder node for the given run number. If it does not exist it is created.
        Parameters:
        runNumber - a run number, or ALLRUNS for the "All Runs" node.
        Returns:
        run folder node, eg: "Run 1", "Run 2", .... "All Runs" etc.

      • getGroupSubFolderNode

        public SubFolderNode getGroupSubFolderNode(String path)
        Gets a SubFolderNode child group subfolder. If it doesn't exist, it is created.
        Parameters:
        path - a path to a sub folder node, eg: "Base/Means" which represents the folder Means under the folder Base, or just "Base" which will add to the folder Base, or null or empty string to get this node.
        Returns:
        group node
